window.docContents[191].resolve({"/Analytic-Number-Theory/The-Selberg-sieve/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Analytic-Number-Theory--The-Selberg-sieve--Fundamental-upper-bound-inequality-of-the-Selberg-sieve":{"contents":"(Fundamental upper-bound-sieve inequality.) Let  be any upper-Möbius weight system,\ni.e. real numbers with  such that \nfor all  (where ). Then the sifted sum () is\nbounded by a main term plus a remainder term:\n\nThe Selberg sieve optimises the choice of  to minimise the resulting main term.\n\nThe defining property of an upper-Möbius system is that  dominates the\nindicator  (IsUpperMoebius). Bounding the sifted sum termwise by this larger\nquantity and exchanging the order of summation expresses\n,\nusing  (multSum_eq_main_err). Splitting off\nthe density part as the main term and bounding the rest by  gives the\ninequality; this is mathlib's siftedSum_le_mainSum_errSum_of_upperMoebius, built on the basic\nsiftedSum_le_sum_of_upperMoebius. It is the engine behind upper-bound sieve estimates such as the\nBrun–Titchmarsh inequality ().\n\n","context":"AINTLIB — An Atlas of Number Theory in Lean\u0009Analytic Number Theory\u0009The Selberg sieve","header":"2.6.2. Fundamental upper-bound inequality of the Selberg sieve","id":"/Analytic-Number-Theory/The-Selberg-sieve/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Analytic-Number-Theory--The-Selberg-sieve--Fundamental-upper-bound-inequality-of-the-Selberg-sieve"},"/Class-Field-Theory-and-Galois-Theory/Group-cohomology___-Tate-cohomology___-Herbrand-quotients___-and-local-CFT/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Class-Field-Theory-and-Galois-Theory--Group-cohomology___-Tate-cohomology___-Herbrand-quotients___-and-local-CFT--The-Reciprocity-Isomorphism-of-a-Class-Formation":{"contents":"(Reciprocity isomorphism of a class formation.) Let  be a finite group and let  be a\n-module equipped with a class  making  a finite class\nformation (so cup product with  induces the cohomology isomorphisms of Tate's theorem). Then\nthere is a canonical isomorphism\n\nbetween the -th Tate cohomology of  and the abelianisation of .\nFormalised in ClassFieldTheory: Rep.split.reciprocityIso — sorry-free.\n\nThis is the abstract engine of class field theory (Tate's theorem), formalised independently of any\narithmetic. From the class formation hypothesis the splitting module of  has trivial\ncohomology, so the connecting maps of the splitting short exact sequence are isomorphisms in all\ndegrees (). Dimension-shifting by two via these isomorphisms identifies\n with , which is the first group homology\n of the trivial module. Composing these canonical\nisomorphisms produces the stated reciprocity isomorphism.\n\n","context":"AINTLIB — An Atlas of Number Theory in Lean\u0009Class Field Theory and Galois Theory\u0009Group cohomology, Tate cohomology, Herbrand quotients, and local CFT","header":"4.6.4. The Reciprocity Isomorphism of a Class Formation","id":"/Class-Field-Theory-and-Galois-Theory/Group-cohomology___-Tate-cohomology___-Herbrand-quotients___-and-local-CFT/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Class-Field-Theory-and-Galois-Theory--Group-cohomology___-Tate-cohomology___-Herbrand-quotients___-and-local-CFT--The-Reciprocity-Isomorphism-of-a-Class-Formation"},"/Elementary-Number-Theory/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Elementary-Number-Theory":{"contents":"This chapter covers the elementary core of number theory as it is formalised in mathlib: divisibility and the Euclidean algorithm, the fundamental theorem of arithmetic, congruences and the structure of the residue rings , arithmetic functions and Dirichlet convolution, quadratic residues and reciprocity, and the classical Diophantine results on sums of squares, Pythagorean triples, and Fermat and Mersenne numbers. Throughout,  denotes a prime,  the integers, and for a positive integer  we write  for the ring of integers modulo  and  for its group of units. Every proof sketch below follows the argument used in the cited mathlib declaration, naming the lemmas that proof actually invokes.\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n","context":"AINTLIB — An Atlas of Number Theory in Lean","header":"1. Elementary Number Theory","id":"/Elementary-Number-Theory/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Elementary-Number-Theory"}});